---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

// CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved

const data = {
  metaTitle: 'Prescription Tracker & Medication Reminder App — All Webbed Labs',
  metaDescription: 'How we helped a Perth compounding pharmacy build a Flutter patient app with medication reminders, adherence tracking and pharmacy system integration — improving patient adherence rates by 44% and earning a 4.8-star app store rating.',
  industry: 'Healthcare',
  tags: ['Flutter', 'FastAPI', 'Firebase Push Notifications', 'Pharmacy Integration', 'Chronic Disease'],
  title: 'Prescription Tracker & Medication Reminder App',
  summary: 'A Perth compounding pharmacy serving 2,400 chronic disease patients was watching treatment gaps happen in slow motion — patients running out of medication, calling in a panic, waiting for reorder. We built a mobile app that changed when and how patients thought about their prescriptions.',
  heroImageDescription: 'Phone screen showing the medication schedule view with upcoming refill reminders and a dose confirmation checklist, alongside the pharmacist dashboard showing active patient adherence',

  clientOverview: 'A compounding pharmacy in Perth operating for eighteen years, specialising in customised medications for patients with chronic conditions — including hormonal compounding, pain management formulations and paediatric preparations. The pharmacy serves approximately 2,400 active patients, many of whom have complex dosing regimens involving multiple compounded medications. Six pharmacists and four dispensary technicians operate the practice, which has built its reputation on the personalised relationship between pharmacist and patient.',
  clientSize: '6 pharmacists, 4 dispensary technicians, ~2,400 active patients',
  clientLocation: 'Perth, WA',

  pullQuote: 'We always said our point of difference was the relationship with the patient. This app extends that relationship into their daily life without requiring us to be on the phone with them every second day.',
  pullQuoteAuthor: 'Pharmacy Owner & Principal Pharmacist',
  pullQuoteRole: 'Perth Compounding Pharmacy',

  challenge: [
    'Compounding pharmacies occupy an unusual position in the medication supply chain. Unlike retail pharmacies that dispense off-the-shelf products, compounding pharmacies make medications from scratch to a specific formulation for a specific patient. This means the patient\'s medication doesn\'t exist until the pharmacy makes it — and making it takes time. Typically 24 to 72 hours depending on the formulation. If a patient waits until they\'ve run out to reorder, there is an unavoidable gap in their treatment.',
    'For many of the pharmacy\'s patients, these gaps were not a minor inconvenience. Patients managing hormone replacement therapy, chronic pain, or paediatric neurological conditions experienced real clinical consequences when their medication ran out. The pharmacy\'s owner had been dealing with distressed calls from patients who\'d run out for years, and the emotional weight of those calls — knowing that the problem was often preventable — had made addressing it a priority.',
    'The existing reminder system was a paper sticker on each dispensed container: "Reorder by [date]." This system had several failure modes. Patients ignored the sticker, forgot to look at it, or couldn\'t remember whether they\'d already reordered. Some patients had multiple compounded medications with different reorder windows and found it genuinely difficult to track all of them. The pharmacy had also tried sending reminder letters by post, but the lead time on postal delivery made this unreliable for time-sensitive reorders.',
    'On the pharmacy side, the reorder-chasing process consumed significant staff time. Pharmacists and dispensary technicians were making outbound calls each week to patients who appeared to be overdue for a reorder based on their last dispense date and their typical usage rate. These calls were individually valuable — patients appreciated the personal contact — but they were coming from the busiest clinical staff during peak dispensing hours, and the time cost was meaningful.',
    'There was also a clinical opportunity the pharmacy was not capturing. The pharmacists had a good intuitive sense of which patients were adhering well and which weren\'t, but no data to support or challenge that intuition. If a patient was consistently reordering every five weeks when their prescription was meant to last four, were they missing doses, or stretching the medication, or experiencing side effects they hadn\'t mentioned? Without data, there was no way to have that conversation proactively.',
  ],

  whyUs: [
    'The pharmacy owner had been thinking about building an app for two years before contacting us. She\'d been put off by quotes from other developers that came with either an unrealistically low price and a template product, or an enterprise-level budget that didn\'t fit a business of her size. She found us through a referral from another small healthcare business that had used us for a different project.',
    'The conversation that convinced her was when we spent most of our first meeting discussing what the app should not do. She\'d collected a long wishlist over two years of thinking about it, and several items on the list — telehealth video, full electronic health record integration, AI-driven dosing recommendations — were either out of regulatory scope for a pharmacy app or would have multiplied the complexity and cost without proportionate benefit for her patients. We helped her separate the features that would directly address the adherence and reorder problem from those that were interesting but not necessary in version one. She appreciated the honesty.',
  ],

  approach: [
    'We ran patient interviews before writing a specification. The pharmacy owner helped us recruit eight patients who were willing to spend 30 minutes on a video call discussing their experience managing their medications. The interviews were illuminating in ways we hadn\'t anticipated. The most common frustration was not "I forget to reorder" — it was "I know I should reorder but I don\'t know exactly when, and I\'m anxious about ordering too early because I think I\'m wasting money." This insight changed our approach to the refill reminder timing: rather than sending a single reminder on a fixed date, we built a sliding window reminder that escalated gently, started with a reassuring message about typical lead times, and was explicitly framed as "order now to avoid a gap" rather than "you\'re running low."',
    'We chose Flutter for the patient-facing app primarily because the patient demographic spans a wide age range — from parents managing paediatric medications to older adults managing chronic conditions — and Flutter\'s ability to deploy to both iOS and Android from a single codebase with consistent UI behaviour was important. The pharmacy could not practically support two divergent native codebases. We also built the app to function largely offline, with sync happening in the background, because we\'d heard in the patient interviews that some patients lived in areas with patchy mobile coverage.',
    'The pharmacy\'s dispensing software — a specialist pharmacy management system used widely in Australian compounding pharmacies — had an API that was documented but not widely used by third parties. We spent considerable time reverse-engineering the actual behaviour of that API from the documentation before building the integration, because the documentation had several inaccuracies. We were explicit with the pharmacy owner about this: the integration was possible but would require ongoing maintenance if the dispensing software updated its API, and we built monitoring alerts to catch any future breaking changes.',
    'Firebase Cloud Messaging was our choice for push notifications, with Twilio SMS as a fallback for patients who disabled push notifications or used devices where FCM wasn\'t reliable. This two-channel approach was important for a healthcare application: a patient who has disabled app notifications might still receive an SMS that prompts them to reorder. We were careful to give patients control over their notification preferences, including the ability to set quiet hours — a feature the older patient cohort in particular requested during the prototype review.',
  ],

  solution: [
    'The patient app is organised around a single primary view: "Your Medications." Each medication is represented as a card showing the medication name (simplified from the clinical formulation name, with the full name available on tap), the current estimated supply remaining (calculated from the last dispense date, the dispensed quantity, and the prescribed dosing schedule), and the next recommended reorder date. The visual representation uses a simple fill-level indicator rather than a numerical countdown — this tested better with older patients in prototype reviews.',
    'Dose reminders are optional and configurable. Patients who want to use the app purely for reorder management can do so; those who want daily dose reminders can set them per medication. We made this distinction explicit during onboarding because we found in our patient interviews that some patients resented dose reminders — they felt infantilising — while others found them genuinely useful. Giving patients agency over this feature increased adoption of the app overall.',
    'Reorder requests are submitted directly through the app. The patient taps "Request Refill," confirms the prescription details, and the request appears in the pharmacist dashboard immediately. For patients who have a current valid prescription on file, reorders can be processed the same day. For patients who need a new prescription, the app prompts them to contact their prescribing doctor and provides a reminder of when their prescription expires. This prescription expiry visibility was a feature the pharmacists specifically requested — patients running out of prescription validity was a common cause of dispense delays they found frustrating.',
    'The pharmacist dashboard is a web application — separate from the patient app — that shows active patients, upcoming reorders, adherence flags, and a simple daily workflow. Pharmacists can see at a glance which patients are overdue for a reorder based on their expected usage pattern versus their actual reorder history. This replaced the manual weekly call process: instead of calling a list of patients based on a guess about who might be running low, pharmacists now work from a prioritised list of patients who data suggests are at risk of a treatment gap.',
    'The dispensing software integration means that when a dispense is completed in the pharmacy\'s existing system, it automatically updates the patient\'s estimated supply in the app. Pharmacists don\'t need to update the app separately; the integration handles the data sync. This was essential for adoption: if maintaining the app had required any additional data entry from the pharmacy staff, it would not have been sustained.',
  ],

  implementation: [
    'We ran a three-month pilot with a subset of 200 patients before opening the app to the full patient base. The pilot patients were recruited by the pharmacy team from patients who had expressed frustration with the existing reminder system. The pilot gave us real-world data on notification timing — we found that evening reminders (7pm) had a 34% higher open rate than morning reminders, and that reminders on Sundays were more likely to result in same-day reorder requests than weekday reminders. We adjusted the default notification settings based on this data before the full rollout.',
    'Patient onboarding was handled by the pharmacy team directly at the point of dispensing. When a patient picked up a medication, the dispensing technician offered to set them up on the app before they left — demonstrating on the patient\'s own phone if they were willing. This in-person onboarding approach resulted in 89% of patients setting up notifications during their first session, which was significantly higher than the typical rate for pharmacy apps that rely on a "download and figure it out yourself" approach.',
    'The dispensing software API integration required more ongoing attention than we\'d estimated in the initial scope. The software vendor released two updates in the first six months that changed response formats in ways that weren\'t backwards-compatible. Our monitoring alerts caught both within an hour, and we were able to deploy fixes before patients experienced any visible disruption. We\'ve since built a more robust version mapping layer that should tolerate minor format changes without requiring immediate patches.',
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    'The framing of reminders matters enormously in healthcare applications. Our early prototypes used reminder language that patients described as "nagging" or "anxious." Working with the pharmacy owner to reframe the language — from "You\'re running low on [medication]" to "Your [medication] will be ready to reorder in about 5 days — this gives you time before your supply runs out" — produced measurably better response rates in the pilot. The clinical content was identical. The emotional framing changed the behaviour.',
    'We initially planned to include a full medication information section — clinical details, side effects, interactions. After consulting with the pharmacy owner and taking legal advice, we removed this entirely. A compounding pharmacy operates in a space where every formulation is specific to a patient\'s prescription, and generic medication information from a third-party database could be actively misleading. The app does one thing related to clinical information: it surfaces the patient\'s own dosing schedule as provided by their pharmacist. Everything else is the pharmacist\'s job.',
    'The offline-first architecture we built for the app turned out to be used more than we\'d expected, and not just by patients in regional areas. Many patients looked at their medication schedule first thing in the morning before turning off airplane mode, or checked their supply estimates while in the pharmacy itself (where connectivity was sometimes poor). Building for offline first, with sync as the expected mechanism rather than the fallback, made the app feel faster and more reliable across all conditions.',
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    'The pharmacy is exploring a pharmacist-facing mobile app that would let pharmacists flag patients for follow-up from their phone during quiet periods, rather than having to be at the dispensary workstation. This is in early design. The owner is also in conversation with two other compounding pharmacies in WA about licensing the platform — a possibility we\'d flagged as a future option when we designed the multi-tenancy architecture from the start, even though the initial deployment was for a single practice.',
    'There is a longer-term discussion about integrating with general practice systems so that prescribers can see their patients\' reorder history and adherence patterns directly, with patient consent. This would require more substantial technical and governance work but would meaningfully close the loop between prescriber, pharmacist and patient.',
  ],

  resultsNarrative: 'The adherence improvement was the headline result, but what the pharmacy team valued most was the change in the nature of their patient interactions. The anxious reorder calls — often received Friday afternoon when the pharmacy was at its busiest — dropped dramatically. The conversations that remained were clinically meaningful: questions about formulations, side effect concerns, dosing questions. The app handled the logistics so the pharmacists could focus on the clinical relationship.',

  metrics: [
    { value: '44%', label: 'Improvement in adherence rate', context: 'Measured by reduction in treatment gaps >2 days across active patients' },
    { value: '380', label: 'Average monthly active users', context: 'Out of 2,400 patient base; 16% adoption rate at 6 months' },
    { value: '0.8 days', label: 'Average reorder gap', context: 'Down from 4.2 days average gap before app launch' },
    { value: '3 hrs/wk', label: 'Pharmacist time saved on reorder chasing', context: 'Previous manual outbound call process replaced by dashboard workflow' },
    { value: '89%', label: 'Notification setup rate at first login', context: 'Driven by in-person onboarding at point of dispensing' },
    { value: '4.8/5', label: 'App store rating', context: 'Combined iOS App Store and Google Play Store average' },
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: 'Flutter', reason: 'Single codebase for iOS and Android; consistent UI across wide device and OS range in patient demographic' },
    { name: 'FastAPI', reason: 'Python backend with async support for push notification scheduling and dispensing software sync' },
    { name: 'PostgreSQL', reason: 'Patient records, prescription history, reorder events and adherence tracking data' },
    { name: 'Firebase Cloud Messaging', reason: 'Cross-platform push notification delivery with delivery receipts and quiet-hours support' },
    { name: 'Twilio SMS', reason: 'Fallback notification channel for patients who disable push notifications' },
    { name: 'Pharmacy Dispensing Software API', reason: 'Automatic supply-level updates triggered by dispense events in the existing pharmacy system' },
    { name: 'AWS (Sydney region)', reason: 'Hosting and patient data storage; Sydney region for healthcare data sovereignty' },
  ],

  relatedCaseStudies: [
    {
      title: 'Patient Management & Appointment System',
      href: '/case-studies/patient-management-appointment-system',
      industry: 'Healthcare',
      summary: 'A Melbourne multi-specialist clinic replaced paper appointment books, fax referrals and disconnected billing with a fully integrated digital practice management platform.',
    },
    {
      title: 'Telehealth Platform for GP Practice',
      href: '/case-studies/telehealth-platform-gp',
      industry: 'Healthcare',
      summary: 'A Brisbane GP practice extended its reach to regional Queensland patients through a Medicare-compliant telehealth platform handling 300+ consultations per week.',
    },
    {
      title: 'Café Loyalty & Rewards App',
      href: '/case-studies/cafe-loyalty-rewards-app',
      industry: 'Hospitality',
      summary: 'A 12-location café franchise launched a branded loyalty app that drove a 27% increase in repeat visits within the first six months.',
    },
  ],

  relatedServices: [
    { title: 'Flutter Development', href: '/services/flutter-development' },
    { title: 'Custom App Development', href: '/services/custom-app-development' },
    { title: 'Healthcare Software', href: '/services/healthcare-software' },
    { title: 'API Development & Integration', href: '/services/api-development' },
  ],
};
